Description: Name of a legacy tutorial objective

en: Welcome to the basic weapons tutorial.
Today, we will be covering weapon configuration, target acquisition, and firing weapons.
Let's start by setting the MFDs to the pages we will use.
The EQUIP page shows what you have on each of the vehicle's equipment mounts.
It displays information on each item, and allows you to arm/disarm, configure, or mark them for jettison.
We'll go over each feature in more detail later.
The TGP is what you will use to acquire ground targets.
To use it, first you must supply power to the sensor mounted under the nose of the vehicle.
The TGP will be in FWD mode by default, which just looks straight forward.
To be able to control it, you must designate the TGP as the sensor of interest (SOI).
Now, you can slew the targeting sensor around using the thumb control on your joystick.
Try slewing the TGP around using the joystick thumb control.
When you move the sensor, it will auto switch to TGT mode, which locks its focus point on the ground while you're flying.
The yellow arrow on the screen shows the relative bearing to the target point.
The target point also shows up on the NAV map as a yellow cross.
Now let's find some targets.  Take off and fly to the objective waypoint.
Now that we are in the AO, you can enable the Master Arm switch.
With the weapon system armed, you will see some new icons on the HUD
At the center, you have the weapon targeting reticle or pipper.
Here, you have weapon type, name, and shots remaining.
You can cycle through all ARMED weapons by pressing the button on the joystick.
These unguided weapons can be fired by simply pulling the trigger on the joystick.
You have limited stores so save your rounds for the targets.
Let's try deploying the GAU-8 on some ground targets.
In a moment, you'll receive a mission objective.
You can auto-slew your TGP to the objective waypoint by pressing the WPT button in the TGP screen.
Go ahead and destroy the tanks.
Great job!  Now let's work with rockets.
By default, each pull of the trigger will fire one rocket.
However, they can be configured to launch rapidly.  This is called 'ripple' firing.
To access a weapons config menu, set the EQUIP MFD page to CONFIG mode
Then, select the weapon you want to configure.
If you have multiple of the same weapon, the settings will be copied over to all of them.
Try setting the rockets to different ripple intervals and destroy the next set of targets.
Well done! You've destroyed all of the targets.
This concludes the basic weapons tutorial.

en: First, let's keep the bird from rolling away.
Now lets move on to the start-up sequence.
Let the APU spool up a bit.
Wait for the engines to spool up.
The engines are now supplying power.  We can turn off the APU.
The HUD (Heads-Up Display) shows you attitude, altitude, velocity, targeting reticles, and other important flight data at a glance.
The MFDs (Multi-Function Displays) give you access to
aircraft features such as weapon configuration, navigation maps,
sensors, etc.  You can access these features by pressing the corresponding buttons around the edge of the monitor.
The vehicle is now ready to fly.  Up next: Basic Flight

Description: Name of a legacy tutorial objective

en: Welcome to the Basic Flight tutorial.
We'll skip the start-up procedure now.
The main flight controls are the joystick and throttle.  You can grip them by holding the grip buttons, or toggle lock your hands to them by tapping the grip buttons.
To steer the front wheel, you will have to twist the joystick on the vertical axis.
In order to get moving, we need to tilt the engines to the forward position.
Hold the throttle trigger to lock the brakes
Then press and hold up on the throttle thumb control to tilt the engines forward.
If you release the brakes and slightly lift the throttle lever, you will start to roll.
Apply small amounts of throttle or brakes to control your speed.
Full stop!  Throttle down and hold the throttle brake trigger.
Let's prepare for a conventional take-off.
Set the brake lock so you can free up your hands.
Make sure all flight assists are enabled
Check that the engines are tilted all the way forward.
Now grab the throttle and hold the brakes...
Now.. to take off, raise the throttle to full and steer to keep aligned with the runway.
Speed up to [80]! Straight down the runway!
Now carefully rotate the joystick back to pull the nose up!
Now gently steer your nose to about 20 degrees and keep climbing to {1000} ASL.
Rotate the joystick left or right to roll towards your target
Rotate the joystick forward or back to pitch your nose towards it.
This is your velocity vector, showing the direction you are moving.
You want to steer velocity vector towards where you want to go.
Great flying! Now let's try to land at the airbase.
Start your landing here at about [150]
Line up with the runway and bring speed down to about [100]
Flaps down, gear down.  Speed down to [80]
Maintain speed and glide slope.  Keep the vector on target!
Prepare to flare nose up for a smooth landing
Touch down! Bring your nose down.
Steer down the runway, throttle down and carefully apply brakes.
Congratulations!  This concludes the basic flight tutorial.

Description: Name of a legacy tutorial objective

en: Welcome to the Vertical Flight autopilot training.
Vertical flight can be tricky, but by using the AP, you will be a master in no time.
First, make sure the engines are tilted at 90 degrees.
First, make sure the engines are tilted at 90 degrees.
The HVR mode will assist you in staying upright and keeping your horizontal velocity under control.
The ALT mode will take control of the engines and convert inputs into climb or descent rates.
Keeping your throttle centered will hold a hover
Raise or lower the throttle to climb or descend
Keep your left thumb away from the tilt control.
Any engine tilt less than 90 will disengage HVR AP
Lift throttle now.  Climb to {50} altitude.
Now set your throttle lever to the midpoint to hover.
You should now be in a stable hover
You can make adjustments to the throttle to climb or descend as needed.
Now you can use the joystick to move around
The HVR autopilot will handle attitude control
You just have to tilt the joystick in the direction you want to go
You can also twist the joystick to yaw
As you move around, study how the AP handles the vehicle
Let's try flying into some targets.
Great! Now lets try to land back on the helipad.
Bring yourself to a stop by centering the throttle, and steering the stick in the opposite direction as your horizontal velocity indicator.
Rotate to face towards the helipads.
Begin to move towards the pad.  Adjust your altitude control and steer so your velocity vector is pointed just above the pad.
Slow your forward speed and rate of descent.
Adjust rate of descent to bring it down gently.
Touch down!  Throttle down and enable brake locks.
Congratulations!  Next time: Manual vertical flight and transitioning.

Description: Short description of playable vehicle AV-42C
en: "Kestrel" Multi-role VTOL aircraft. Tilting jet nozzles give it the ability to take off and land vertically or horizontally. Large cargo bay and multiple weapon mounts allow for both transport and attack missions.

Description: Short description of playable vehicle F/A-26B
en: "Wasp" Carrier based air-superiority fighter that can also be configured for ground attack roles.

Description: Short description of playable vehicle F-45A
en: "Ghost" Stealthy, single-engine, VTOL/STOVL capable aircraft with four internal bays. Optional external hardpoints can be used to increase carrying capacity when stealth is not needed.
Help make preparations to defend the island. Transport personnel to coastal SAM site.
Let the soldiers into your passenger bay.
Drop the soldiers off at the east bay SAM site.
Join up with the fighter escort wing.
Pick up the survivors from the crash site.
Deliver the survivors to the hospital.
Return to and land at the airbase.
Allow the fighters to clear out the hostile drones.
Destroy the drone ships laying mines on supply routes.
Meet up with Victor1 at the waypoint.
Lead the strike group to the area of operations.
If able, support your wingmen by destroying the carrier's weapons and drones.
Join the carrier fleet embarking on a pre-emptive naval strike.
Search for the lost pilot near the objective waypoint.
Lead the lost pilot to the refuel tanker.
Lead the pilot to the aircraft carrier.
Meet the enemy in open water for a pre-emptive strike.
Help defend the fleet from the incoming drones.
Destroy or disable all enemy weapon systems, sensors, and drones.
Return to the fleet and land.
Return to the island to investigate why communications have gone silent.
Take off and fly to the aerial fuel tanker.
Allow Romeo1-2 to refuel. Then you may refuel yourself if necessary.
Avoid the enemy fleet. Return to the waypoint and await orders.
Destroy the armored units moving toward our allied infantry.
Begin a counterattack under the cover of darkness.
Take off and prepare for your anti-ship strike.
Destroy the long range missile cruiser.
Begin to take back the island and eliminate the enemy fleet off the northern coast.
Destroy the incoming enemy carrier fleet.
Clear out the enemy units at the airbase.
Destroy the enemy SAM site to allow reinforcements to take off.
Rearm if necessary, then regroup with Victor 1.
Destroy the rocket-equipped drone boats threatening the carrier.
Destroy the carrier group's radars and air defenses so bombers can come to help.

Negotiations for peace have failed.  We believe the enemy will strike here first, as a stepping stone to the mainland.

We have begun preparing coastal air defenses.

As an AV-42C pilot, you will deliver personnel to the defense sites.

Other pilots and soldiers will be arriving by air from the mainland soon.
As we continue to prepare our defenses against the invasive enemy forces, we need to secure supply routes from the mainland to the island.
The troops you recovered from the crash site reported that they spotted what seemed to be unmanned vessels deploying sea mines near the south east supply route.

You will lead a strike group with the order of destroying all hostile targets in the designated area.  

Prepare your aircraft appropriately.
Our engineers were able to salvage the navigation computers from the drone ships and used them to determine the location of the main naval fleet of the enemy.
We have tasked an aircraft carrier fleet to intercept before they get too close to the island.  In order to maximize their force, you and other pilots are ordered to join the fleet.

A pilot belonging to the carrier was out on combat air patrol when his navigation systems experienced a failure.  The pilot is lost and low on fuel, so you must quickly find him and lead him to the fuel tanker on the way to the carrier.

We have intercepted the enemy fleet sooner than we expected to. They have already deployed aerial drones which are heading towards our fleet. All units are to scramble to defend the fleet, as well as quickly launch a counter-attack.

The enemy force is numerous and includes small drone boats, missile cruisers, and drone carriers. This is going to get messy.

Good luck.

We received an encrypted message from the island airbase which suggested that a large presence was detected coming in from the north.

After that, all communications went silent.

The captain is worried that the enemy fleet we just attacked was just a diversion, and a larger enemy fleet somehow sailed to the island undetected.

We are returning to the island to investigate the radio silence.

We are conserving on-board jet fuel in anticipation of responding to the potential threat, so the fighter escorts will need to refuel in the air.

Once everyone is topped off, scout the island and report back.  Good luck.

On the scouting sortie, a large enemy fleet was detected north of the island.  The enemy has also begun landing ground units on the island.

Before we can begin to move in and take back the island, we need to eliminate the threat posed by the enemy long range missile cruiser.

The cruiser has an array of launch tubes which we believe are capable of deploying two-stage surface-to-air and anti-ship missiles.  It also has a vertical launching system defense cannons, so it may not be effective to use conventional bombs or air-to-ground missiles.

In order to take out the threat, we are authorizing the use of the AGM-89 anti-ship cruise missile.  It has advanced features such as waypoint navigation, radar target acquisition, and a large payload.  Use it wisely and destroy the high priority target.

The mission launches at midnight. You will be escorted by a small wing of fighters to defend you from airborne threats.

The enemy has likely deployed more self-propelled SAM units to the island, so keep an eye out for missile launches and radar locks.

Good luck.

With the destruction of the enemy fleet's most powerful ship, we can begin an effort to take back the island.

Through the night, the enemy has continued to deploy troops and set up defenses around the island.

The first order is to clear out enemy units from the island airbase. Air defenses have been set up, so be prepared to use the surrounding hills for cover.

Once the airbase has been cleared, we can use it for refueling and rearming.

Once that is out of the way, we must eliminate the rest of the enemy fleet parked off the norther coast.

An allied carrier fleet is arriving from the east to support us, but are unable to launch aircraft due to enemy air defenses in the eastern city.

Destroy the eastern air defenses to allow the allied pilots to take off, then make a combined effort to destroy the enemy fleet.

The allied fleet will also move into firing range to support with anti-ship missiles.
Quick flights and practice scenarios for the AV-42C.
Free flight on a custom map.
Practice refueling in the air. Remember to lower your starting fuel.
Practice landing on the carrier or one of the cruisers.
Land on the carrier or one of the cruisers.
No objectives or hostiles.  Just fly around and have fun!
This is a free flight, however, landing on the carrier will complete the mission
Practice using different weapons on multiple groups of non-hostile targets.
Destroy the artillery on the edge of the south-eastern city.
Eliminate the enemy infantry squad patrolling near the hospital
Destroy the armored convoy moving west from the eastern city.
Destroy the air defense network on the mountain peak.
Destroy the wing of enemy attack aircraft.
Just fly around and have fun!
A tanker is available for A2A refuelling.
Try landing on one of the ships!
Practice refueling in the air. Remember to lower your starting fuel, or else the tanker won't bother lowering the boom.

Practice landing on the ships.  For the carrier, you can land vertically or with the arrestor cables.

The carrier will be moving from east to west.  Use the NAV screen on the MFD to aid you in your approach.

There are no objectives. Just fly around and have fun!

There is an aircraft carrier at sea and an aerial refueling tanker in the sky.

There are multiple groups of surface and air targets for you to practice on.

Check the waypoints and information in the Objectives MFD page.
Several ground and air targets to practice deploying your weapons on. Targets will not shoot back.
Destroy the column of vehicles crossing the bridge.
Destroy the bomber and its escorts flying at high altitude.
Destroy the radar network around the central mountains.
Destroy the vertical take-off attack jets coming from the FARP.
Land at any of the airbases or aircraft carrier.
Take on two enemy fighters with your wingman.
Surprise! More fighters to kill. Where will they come from?
Practice landing on the aircraft carrier.
A variety of hostile targets to destroy.  Practice using the aircraft as a fighter, a striker, or a mix of both.
Destroy the enemy fire control radars around south city.
Destroy the naval group to the east.
Search for and destroy enemy fighters.
Refuel without landing. Fuel must be below 95% for the tanker to serve.
No enemies or objectives.  Just fly around and have fun!
Free flight in the twin-city bay map. No enemies or objectives.

Various air and land targets are scattered around the area. Practice using your sensors and weapons to find and destroy the targets without worrying about them shooting back.

Several airbases and a carrier are available for you to use for rearming and refuelling if necessary.
In this scenario, you will start in the air with a wingman.  Fly towards the island and take out the two enemy fighters.
You will start in the air near the carrier.  Find it, then circle around for a landing approach.

Several enemy air, land, and naval units are scattered around the island.
Complete each of the mission objectives and return to the carrier.
You may need to return to the carrier to refuel and rearm during the mission.
Practice aerial refueling with the F/A-26B.  Make sure to start off with a partially empty fuel tank.  Otherwise, the tanker will not lower to fuel boom.
Just fly around and have fun!
Defend the city from the enemy attack.

An unidentified flying object has been detected over the island.  It appears to be giving off the same signals as those recorded near the recent attacks on mainland cities, so we're assuming hostility.  Find it and destroy it at all cost.
A short campaign for the F/A-26B based around mountainous desert regions.
Defend the airbase supply depots from the incoming enemy attack.
Prevent the enemy from destroying all of the storage depots.
Destroy bomber (HB-106) and 2 escorts (ASF-30) before they destroy the depots.
Destroy 3 strikers (GAV-25), 2 escorts (ASF-30) before they destroy the depots.
Destroy the artillery unit before it does more damage to the depots.
Mission complete!  Land back at the airbase.
Destroy the 2 fighters (ASF-58) before they can take down our AWACs.
Turn the tables and attack the enemy airbases' supplies.
Destroy the enemy depots at the northern airbase.
Mission complete!  Land back at the airbase.
Destroy the enemy depots at the eastern airbase.
Escort a strike group sent to destroy ships at the enemy's naval testing area.
SEAD & protect X-Ray while they complete anti-shipping mission.
Join the group of Anti-Ship strikers.
Protect the bomber while it attacks the remaining ships.
Follow and protect the strike group along the way to the attack waypoint.
Destroy the fighters threatening X-Ray strike group.
Defend a tanker from airborne threats while it rendezvous with allied bombers.
Defend the tanker as it rendezvous with bomber group Sierra.
Defend the tanker and bombers as they refuel and return to base.
Our naval strike group will be departing from port on the western coast. Hostile forces are trying to stop them.
Defend the carrier fleet as it embarks form the  port.
Destroy armored vehicles moving towards the base.
Destroy ground targets moving through the canyons towards the base.
Destroy hostile bomber and its escorts.
Participate in a strike on hostile military targets.
General objective: Fly Combat Air Patrol.
Destroy air targets launching from enemy carrier.
Shift CAP focus to the next waypoint.
Destroy aircraft departing from the enemy airbase.
Destroy enemy bomber and escorts threatening carrier.
Approach the attack waypoint with the other air groups.
The carrier group's next target is one of the enemy's main sources of oil.
Fly to objective waypoint and await further instructions.
Find and destroy the high priority target.
End the conflict for good by launching a heavy strike on the command center.
Follow the wing leader and her commands on the way to the AO.
Destroy all supply depots in the base.
Disable any remaining air defenses around the base.
Protect the transport and the team of soldiers it carries.
Take off and wait for wingmen.
Destroy tanks threatening the raid team.

You are stationed at our most remote airbase, closest to the enemy border.

The enemy seeks to destroy the airbase's supplies in order to prevent us from conducting airstrikes in this region.

Intel has revealed that the enemy has launched a multi-pronged effort to attack the airbase.

A small group of hostile self-propelled artillery have mobilized to get into firing range of our supply depots.

While it will be necessary to destroy the artillery, we believe that the attack is aimed to distract us from a follow-up airstrike.

The type of attackers, their locations, and numbers are unknown at this time.

An E-4 AWACS will be deployed in order to aid in locating the airborne threats.

Due to our proximity to enemy territory, the AWACS will be vulnerable.  Please defend it if necessary.

SUMMARY:
Objective:
Defend airbase supply depots.

Known targets:
3x self-propelled artillery

Unknown targets:
Bombers and/or attack aircraft.

Now's our chance to head back out and return the favor to the enemy.

They occupy two airbases -- one to the northeast, and one further due north.

You must destroy the 4 supply depots at each base, for a total of 8 targets.

The enemy is most likely expecting us, so they probably beefed up air defenses as well as numerous aircraft on patrol.

Use the cover of darkness and terrain to mask your approach to the targets.

We have gathered intel on the near exact locations of their supplies, which will be set as the objective waypoints.

How you want to attack is up to you.
I recommend to remain radar silent to avoid detection.

SUMMARY:
Objective: 
- Destroy the 8 supply depots at each base (4 each).

Threats:
- Numerous radar and IR SAM sites
- Hostile combat air patrol

You've been transferred to the airbase near Gloom Lake.  

This lake lies on another border between our nation and the enemy's, and is where they conduct tests on naval vessels and aircraft.

There have been an unusually high number of enemy drones harassing us recently.  They fly dangerously close to our base and force us to take defensive measures.  

We believe that they're attempting to distract us while they test new military technologies.

In order to put a damper on their research efforts, we're sending out a group of F/A-26Bs configured to sink their test ships.

Although this is a testing area, the enemy ships are fully functional and armed.

You and your wingmen are tasked to destroy enemy air defenses and patrol aircraft, to allow the strikers to perform the anti-shipping attack.

The strikers will be in the air waiting for you.  Join them and escort them along their attack path.

When you reach the end of the attack path, the strikers will begin anti-shipping. Target radars to prevent them from defending against the attack.

Simultaneously, allied combat air patrol will be vectored to the area to help keep enemy aircraft away.

SUMMARY:
Objective: Support strikers while they attack enemy ships.
- Suppress enemy air defenses
- Defend strikers from enemy air patrols

Primary Targets:
- Radars
- Aggressive Aircraft

Threats:
- Ships
- Aircraft
- SAMs
- AAA

A couple of bombers are returning from a long range mission.  Their fuel reserves are low, so we're sending out a KC-49 tanker to provide air-to-air refuelling.

We are concerned that enemy aircraft will intercept the tanker, which is where you and your wingmen come in.

Fly with the tanker and keep it safe. Maintain active radar and RWR so you are aware of hostiles. 

AWACs will also be available to help spot incoming threats.

SUMMARY
Objective: 
- Escort the tanker to the rendezvous.  
- Engage all hostile aircraft that approach.
- Mission complete when the tanker and bombers return to base.

Threats:
- Hostile aircraft

It's time to send a naval strike group deep into enemy territory.  The aircraft carrier and its escorts will soon be ready to depart, but enemy forces are close.  

They will likely attempt to stop the carrier group before our mission can even begin.

Your job is to protect the ships, onboard aircraft, and the naval base from the enemy attack.  Hostile aircraft and land vehicles are approaching.  

Once the coast is clear, you will land on the carrier and join on the offensive.

SUMMARY

Objective:
- Defend naval strike group and naval base

Threats:
- Fighter Aircraft
- Bombers
- Tanks
- Mobile Anti-Air

The carrier group's first stop is a small northern island territory occupied by the enemy.

They have a few military bases here and use the island to stage their attacks on our western coast.

The island is a valuable asset to the enemy's air and naval forces, so it's our duty to halt their operations here.

We will launch a full on air assault.

There are 4 major components to the attack, which will be split up among 4 specialized air groups.

Whiskey group will suppress enemy air defenses. X-ray group will attack ground targets such as armored vehicles and supply depots.  Bravo will sink the enemy ships.

Kilo group, your group, will fly combat air patrol and keep the enemy fighters away from the other groups.

The enemy only has a few groups of fighters in the air, but they have a carrier full of aircraft ready to go, and an airbase not far from our point of entry.
All groups will maintain open communications, but you will only have command over your own group.  Focus on your own objective (CAP) but maintain awareness of the bigger picture.

SUMMARY

Objective:
- Combat air patrol

Targets:
- Multiple hostile aircraft

Threats:
- Hostile Aircraft
- SAMs
- Ships

We have located the enemy's main source of oil off the shore of some remote islands.  

The carrier group has been sent to destroy the oil platforms and further reduce the enemy's ability to fuel war.

There seems to be an unusually high naval military presence here, so the guided missile cruisers will be assisting your attack.

Air groups X-ray and Sierra will be primarily focused on SEAD, while Bravo will provide CAP.

Your group, Kilo, will be responsible for striking the oil platforms.

We need the platforms to be destroyed beyond all repair, so you can either destroy all key components on the platform, or destroy two support pillars to topple the entire platform.

Our cruisers will approach from the north, on the western side of the ridge. 

The air groups will approach on the eastern side of the ridge at low altitude. You should remain undetected until you reach the channel.

The SEAD attack from the east should occur at the same time that the cruiser anti-ship missiles reach the enemy.

This will keep their defenses saturated while Kilo comes in to take down the oil platforms.
There may be other ground targets for you, but we will keep you updated on those as we acquire more information.

SUMMARY

Objective:
- Destroy 4 oil platforms

Threats
- Ships
- SAMs
- Aircraft

This mission will have two phases.
On the first phase, Kilo 1-1 will lead the flight into enemy territory.

You will be Kilo 1-2, and are assigned to support the flight lead.  Execute her commands to destroy secondary targets on the way to the enemy base.

The mission is scheduled to start when one of the enemy's coastal defense sites goes down temporarily.

We expect the defenses to resume operation when they spot your approach, but at least it will give you an opportunity to disable them before they can acquire you.

The flight path will be low, weaving through the valleys to avoid line of sight with enemy radar.

Maintain formation with Kilo 1 for the entirety of the ingress phase.

The secondary targets are coastal defenses at Alpha and two IR SAM units at Bravo. Destroying them will help clear the way for the bomber. 

Again, flight leader Kilo 1-1 will call the shots on these targets.

The primary objective will begin when you reach the base at Charlie.

Allied rocket artillery will be in the area launching strikes on the base's air defenses.

The primary targets are rows of cylindrical tents lined up from east to west.

Your flight path will allow you to strike multiple targets in a single low-altitude bombing pass.
After the first pass, flight lead duties will be passed over to you (Kilo 1-2).  Lead your wingmen to take down the remaining targets.

A group of F-45A's will take off from a nearby FARP to help keep enemy aircraft and other threats off of you and your wingmen.

Once primary targets have been destroyed, an AV-42C will also dispatch from here to deliver troops to the headquarters and capture the enemy leaders.

You will be tasked to protect them at that time, but we'll update you on that final operation when we get to it.

Focus on supporting your wingmen during the flight through hostile territory and destroying the primary targets.

SUMMARY

OBJECTIVES
-  Clear air defenses for bombers
- *Destroy enemy assets
-  Protect troop transport

THREATS
- IR and Radar SAMs
- Aircraft
A small collection of quick missions for the F-45A.
Take the lead on this two-part mission to take down hostile bombers.
Destroy the long range MAD-4 Radar (M4) near the airbase.
Destroy the fighters taking off from the base with the help of India group.
Destroy bombers taking off from second airbase.
Attack high value targets in an attack on enemy territory.
Locate and destroy the command & control bunkers
Destroy the artillery attacking our ships.
Find and destroy the highly capable enemy stealth fighters.
Find and destroy the enemy bomber aircraft.
Do not let the enemy destroy either of our carriers!
Practice arrested or vertical landings on a moving carrier.
Search for and destroy enemy weapon caches. Avoid detection or pay the price. Once they know where you are, they'll do anything to stop you.
Find and destroy enemy weapon caches. Locations unknown.
Return to and land on the helipad.

You will be the first to launch from the carrier.

Destroy the long range air defenses at the enemy coastal airbase Alpha first so that we can launch fighters.
Once the air defenses are destroyed, CAP group India will launch from the carrier to help you clean up the enemy fighters.

After clearing the fighters, land at the FARP to reconfigure for a purely air-to-air role. You will be joined by another F-45 to take down the enemy bombers taking off from airbase Bravo.

SEAD group Romeo will launch from the carrier to disable the SAM sites at Bravo.
Destroy the two bombers from Bravo then return to carrier to complete the mission!

Complete all of the objectives, then return to the assault carrier.

You can complete them in any order you choose.

There's a mix of hardened surface targets and air targets.

Enemy rocket artillery have moved into range and have begun firing on our fleet from the other side of a mountain.

They have a low hit probability, but we must destroy them.
Enemy bombers have also been known to operate from this area. If they decide to deploy them against our assault fleet, they will be a high priority target.
We have little intel on their whereabouts, but a handful of enemy stealth fighters are stationed by the bay and must be destroyed.
Finally, you must find the enemy command post and destroy the two bunkers. The bunkers will likely be adjacent to large supply tents.
Enemy bases are well defended, so use caution when operating near them.
The mission will be considered a failure if either of our carriers are destroyed.

No objectives or enemies.

You will start at 300kts, 1000ft above two carriers.  Contact one of them to request clearance to land.
You are stationed at small FARP (forward arming and refueling point) near an enemy airbase.  Unfortunately, you only have enough supplies for one last sortie, and it's a tough one.

The mission is to destroy 3 enemy weapon caches.  We don't know exactly where they are, but they are most likely near air defenses.  Based on their radar emissions, we have estimated the positions of 4 sites.  The caches may all be at one site, or spread out between them.

You don't have any support on this mission.  No extra fuel, no rearming, no wingmen, nothing.  With scattered SAM sites and numerous enemy air patrols, the odds are stacked against you.  Use stealthy tactics to maneuver around the area and destroy the targets.

SUMMARY:
Objective:
  - Destroy the 3 weapon caches (supply tents)

Threats:
  - SAMs
  - Patrolling aircraft
Learn how to use the cannon, rockets, and targeting system.
Learn how to use the hover autopilot feature.

Today we will be learning how to operate the AV-42C.

The start-up procedure is not very complicated, so let's jump in and get started.

The AV-42C is capable of equipping various weapons.  Today you will learn how to use the 30mm GAU-8 cannon, and the Hydra-70 unguided rockets.  You will also learn how to find and acquire targets using the TGP.
Vertical flight can be tricky, but by using the hover autopilot, you can take off, hover, and land with ease.
Learn how to use air-to-ground missiles.
Destroy some of the targets around the waypoint using the AGM-114.
Learn how to use the cannon, rockets, and targeting system.
Learn how to use the hover autopilot feature.
Today, you will learn how to use air-to-ground missiles (AGMs) to destroy armored ground targets.
Learn how to use the virtual flight controls to taxi, take off, and land the AV-42C "Kestrel".

Today we will be learning how to operate the AV-42C.

The start-up procedure is not very complicated, so let's jump in and get started.

The AV-42C is capable of equipping various weapons.  Today you will learn how to use the 30mm GAU-8 cannon, and the Hydra-70 unguided rockets.  You will also learn how to find and acquire targets using the TGP.
Vertical flight can be tricky, but by using the hover autopilot, you can take off, hover, and land with ease.
Learn how to use the radar to find, track, and lock onto aircraft.
Shoot the target with an AIM-120
Learn how to use the ARAD and AGM-88 to destroy radar targets.
The F/A-26B is equipped with powerful forward facing radar. Learn how to use it to detect and track other aircraft.  Lock onto enemy targets to allow you to fire radar guided missiles.

One of the most abundant and dangerous threats to aircraft are Surface-to-Air Missiles (SAMs), most of which rely on radar to find and track targets.

Suppression of Enemy Air Defense (SEAD) operations neutralize or destroy these threats.

One method of performing SEAD involves destroying the radar used by the SAMs.

You will learn how to use the Anti-Radar Attack Display (ARAD) in conjunction with the AGM-88 weapon to locate, target, and destroy enemy radars.
Pick up the soldiers at the waypoint.
Transport the soldiers to the objective waypoint.
Destroy the enemy units on the road towards our soldiers.
Destroy the units in the city by the landing zone.
Strike enemy artillery. This mission is intended to test the performance of a large custom map.
Form up with your air group and fly the patrol path, MSN-1

en: Welcome to the air-to-ground missile tutorial!
Air-to-ground missiles (AGM) are useful for precisely hitting light to medium armored ground targets
You will use the TGP to designate targets for the AGMs
These are small, laser-guided, anti-tank missiles
Since they home in on the laser point emitted by your TGP, you must maintain line of sight to the target until it hits
To fire it, designate a target using the TGP, point your aircraft at the target until the missile locks on, then pull the trigger to fire
You can also switch the missile seeker's uncage mode to MANUAL, which will allow you to fire at targets off boresight
In MANUAL mode, you hold the trigger to uncage the seeker, then press the weapon switch button to fire
Try shooting the targets around the mission waypoint using the AGM-114
Remember, you need to maintain line of sight with your TGP in order to guide the missile to the target
Great! Now switch to the AGM-65
This is a larger, slightly heavier hitting anti-tank missile with a more advanced optical seeker
With this type of missile, you do not need to maintain a lock on the target after you fire at it
The fire-and-forget capability allows you to fire at multiple targets in one pass, or take cover after firing
Try taking down the targets at the next waypoint and practice taking advantage of the fire-and-forget capability
Nice shooting!  This concludes the air-to-ground missile tutorial
Welcome to the Radar tutorial for the F/A-26
Today, you will learn how to use the radar to find and track other aircraft, as well as designate targets for air to air missiles
The display shows you a compressed representation of the radar's 120 degree field of view
The displayed range can be adjusted using the R+ and R- buttons
Press R+ repeatedly until the display is at max range
As the radar sweeps over other aircraft, they will be displayed as blue icons for friends and orange icons for foes
The left/right SCAN ANGLE can also be adjusted to allow the radar to scan more rapidly but in a smaller slice of the sky
Now, you can slew the target designator using the joystick's thumb control
Slew the designator over a contact, and press in on the center of the thumb control to start tracking it
You can track up to 4 contacts while still being able to scan the rest of the sky
They will appear as small circle on your HUD, along with their corresponding number
In order to lock a target for weapons, click on a track again using the designator, or press the numbered MFD button on the left
While a target is locked, the other tracks will continue to be displayed, but the radar will not be able to scan for new targets
Information about the locked target's bearing, range, altitude, airspeed, and aircraft type will appear on the bottom right of the display
Use the UNLCK button to unlock the target, and the CLR button to clear the tracks
For close in engagements, the radar can be switched to boresight mode using the MODE button
In this mode, the radar will point straight forward and lock onto the first contact it sees
If the radar is SOI, you can press the joystick thumb control to quickly unlock and find a new target
Now for some weapons practice. Go back to scan mode and find, track, and lock the enemy aircraft.
Good. Now arm your weapon system and switch to the AIM-120
On the HUD, the locked target will appear as a small square.  The small dot is the shot lead cue
When firing air to air missiles, aim for the lead cue to help the missile conserve energy as it steers toward the target
The DLZ is displayed on the right side of the HUD. The missile should be fired when the target chevron lies between the min and max marks
By tracking multiple contacts, you can fire up to 4 AIM-120s on separate targets as long as you maintain line of sight with each of them
When the AIM-120's time to impact counter displays the letter M, it has switched to active homing and you no longer need to track it.
Now, try shooting down the rest of the enemy air targets.
Out of missiles!  You hit some of the targets though!
Out of missiles!  You didn't hit anything.  Want to try again?
SEAD stands for Suppression of Enemy Air Defenses
You will use a combination of radar detecting sensors and special weapons to disable SAM sites
When a radar is searching for aircraft, it emits a signal that can be detected by your RWR
The radar type, bearing, and approximate range is shown on the RWR display, relative to your position in the center
This display shows the same information gathered by the RWR, but allows you to select targets for ARMs
You can also set radar sources to be displayed as diamonds in the HUD
When you lower the AR visor, you'll be able to see all of the targets around you for better situational awareness
Now you can use your joystick thumb control to slew the targeting cursor
Slew the cursor onto the enemy radar, then press in on the thumb control to set the target
A square will appear on the selected target in both the MFD and the HUD
This is a high speed, fire-and-forget anti-radiation missile (ARM)
When fired, it will home in on the radar source designated in the ARAD
Once you have a target selected, all you need to do is fly toward the target, and fire once the missile is in range
Try taking out the SAM radars using the AGM-88
Great!  This is the end of the SEAD tutorial.
